body:
While trying to benchmark how long it takes to naively find the number of months between 2 dates with chrono, I ran into an issue with iterators. I tried this code:

```rust
#![feature(test)]

use chrono::{DateTime, Datelike, Utc};
use chrono::TimeZone;

extern crate test;

fn inc_year(d: &mut DateTime<Utc>) -> &mut DateTime<Utc> {
    let year = d.clone().year();
    *d = match d.with_year(year + 1) { // overflow error causes `None` to be returned here.
        Some(d) => d,
        None => panic!("Date is {:?}, year is {:?}", *d, year), 
    };
    d
}

fn years_between(d1: &mut DateTime<Utc>, d2: &DateTime<Utc>) -> u64 {
    (0..)
        .skip_while(|_| *inc_year(d1) <= *d2)
        .next()
        .unwrap()
}

#[bench]
fn from0000to2000(b: &mut test::bench::Bencher) {
    let mut date1 = chrono::Utc.ymd(1, 1, 1).and_hms_milli(1, 1, 1, 1);
    let date2 = chrono::Utc.ymd(3, 1, 1).and_hms_milli(1, 1, 1, 1);
    b.iter(|| test::bench::black_box(years_between(&mut date1, &date2)));
 }
```

I expected to see this happen: The infinite iterator should continue up until `inc_year(d1)` is greater than `*d2`, and then it should yield the number for which this is true.

Instead, this happened: Instead I _sometimes_ get error due to integer overflow. To investigate I changed the line with `skip_while` to `.skip_while(|_| dbg!(dbg!(*inc_year(d1)) <= dbg!(*d2)))`. The results are:

```
cargo bench
# ... snip
[src/main.rs:30] *inc_year(d1) = 0003-01-01T01:01:01.001Z
[src/main.rs:30] *d2 = 0003-01-01T01:01:01.001Z
[src/main.rs:30] dbg!(* inc_year(d1)) <= dbg!(* d2) = true
[src/main.rs:30] *inc_year(d1) = 0004-01-01T01:01:01.001Z
[src/main.rs:30] *d2 = 0003-01-01T01:01:01.001Z
[src/main.rs:30] dbg!(* inc_year(d1)) <= dbg!(* d2) = false
# ... snip
```

So the `Ord` implementation on `chrono::DateTime` correctly returns false, but the iterator continues looping.

